WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.320
Occupying the southeastern edge of the 
Arabian Peninsula, seven traditional

00:00:04.320 --> 00:00:09.680
emirates spanning from the Rub Al Khali Desert 
to the Western Hajar Mountains united into an

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:16.240
extraordinary federation. When Britain announced 
its withdrawal from the Gulf in 1971, the rulers

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:21.200
of Abu Dhabi and Dubai first established 
a bilateral union for mutual protection,

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:25.440
then extended invitations to the neighboring 
Emirates to join their alliance, creating what

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:30.880
is today known as the United Arab Emirates. 
Spanning across the eastern outcrop of the

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:36.240
Arabian Peninsula as a jagged crescent, the 
image of this union is often reduced to just a

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:42.160
lot of sand and empty space. While this perception 
isn’t entirely inaccurate, around and underneath

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:46.640
the endless sand dunes and salt flats, there 
are a lot more geographical nuances which we

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:51.680
will have a closer look at in this video. 
Since it is the most prominent feature of

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:55.760
the Emirates, we will start our journey in 
the Rub Al Khali desert before moving along

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:00.160
the coast to then finish our journey in the&nbsp;
eastern mountains at the Gulf of Oman.

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:05.520
The most striking and omnipresent feature of the 
Arabian Peninsula is certainly the Arabian Desert,

00:01:05.520 --> 00:01:12.080
whose southernmost and most desolate section is 
the Rub Al Khali, Arabic for "The Empty Quarter".

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:17.920
The vast expanse remains virtually devoid of 
life both in its Saudi heartland and where it

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:22.400
extends across the border into the Emirates, 
which explains why so little attention has been

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:26.880
paid to precisely demarcating the border
between the two countries in this region.

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:31.840
The Treaty of Jeddah, drafted with Saudi 
Arabia shortly after the UAE's establishment,

00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:36.000
was intended to formalize the federation's 
borders. While the parties reached broad

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.080
agreement on most territorial claims, 
significant uncertainties remain,

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:45.200
with the UAE maintaining that the final written 
treaty differed substantially from the verbal

00:01:45.200 --> 00:01:51.360
agreements reached during negotiations. Allegedly, 
the written demarcation shifts the entire boundary

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:56.960
5 to 15 kilometers northeastward in Saudi Arabia's 
favor, which is why the UAE hasn’t ratified the

00:01:56.960 --> 00:02:02.800
agreement to this day. On first glance, the land 
in question might seem of little value, were it

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:08.400
not for the vast oil deposits found just south 
of Saudi Arabia’s claimed border. Since the 70s,

00:02:08.400 --> 00:02:13.840
the UAE has tried to get Saudi Arabia back to the 
negotiating table to address these discrepancies,

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:19.920
but not much progress has been made and it remains 
a contentious topic between the two nations.

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:25.440
Surrounding this Shaybah Oil field, now maintained 
by Saudi Arabia, topographic mapping reveals

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:30.400
a dramatic shift in the landscape's relief 
compared to the otherwise monotonous desert,

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:36.080
with up to 300 meter tall dunes towering over 
the salt pans. To an even bigger surprise,

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:40.480
the northern boundary of this dune field is 
also bustling with life and development that

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:46.160
seemingly defies the region’s harsh natural 
constraints. Spanning a 120 kilometer long

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:51.840
crescent around the giant sandbox, an ancient 
aquifer allows for date palm plantations,

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:58.320
which has led to a population explosion in recent 
decades. The Liwa Oasis has been populated for

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:03.200
centuries now and is actually the home region 
of Abu Dhabi's ruling family, but only with

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:08.640
advancements in well technology has this level of 
development become feasible here. The excessive

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:14.560
growth doesn’t come without its downsides though 
and today the roughly 40.000 inhabitants spread

00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:19.840
over 50 villages are living well above their 
means when it comes to the water reserve.

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:24.800
An unconfined clay basin around 110 meters 
underground has collected monsoon rains

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:29.520
from around 9 to 6 thousand years ago, but since 
then, there has been virtually no replenishment.

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:31.200
of the aquifer.

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:36.240
Realizing this discrepancy in the water balance but 
not wanting to give up on the primary agricultural

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:41.920
zone of the country, the Abu Dhabi government 
is keen on artificially sustaining the aquifer.

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:46.880
Massive pipelines have been constructed for this 
purpose, which channel excess desalinated water

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:53.200
from the coastal plants into the hinterland of 
the UAE, attempting to sustain the water table.

00:03:53.200 --> 00:03:58.880
Nevertheless, the scale of extraction far outpaces&nbsp;
replenishment and the projection of even more

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:04.800
growth in the region makes this project but a token&nbsp;
gesture against the harsh hydrological reality.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:09.920
Beyond the underground aquifers, life is harsh&nbsp;
in the Rub al Khali Desert, with only a handful

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:15.760
of plant and animal species able to tolerate the&nbsp;
extreme aridity. Summer temperatures in the desert

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:23.200
frequently reach highs of 48° Celsius or 113°&nbsp;
Fahrenheit and regular Sharqi Wind in spring

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:29.680
and autumn suspend sand and dust into kilometer&nbsp;
tall towers that sweep across the desert. Among

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:36.400
the few mammals adapted to these conditions is&nbsp;
the Arabian Oryx, once hunted to near extinction

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:42.400
but now making a steady recovery within a large&nbsp;
protected reserve along the desert's outskirts.

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:47.760
Most of the UAE’s fauna is not found on land but&nbsp;
rather along the sandy shoreline and surrounding

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:53.360
the many islands in the Persian Gulf. The high&nbsp;
temperatures which make the land barely habitable

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:58.480
are also threatening the ocean health, but many&nbsp;
hundreds of species have adapted to the water

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:05.120
temperature exceeding 36° on a regular basis.
Especially in front of the coast of Abu Dhabi,

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:10.320
4% of the global seagrass meadows can be&nbsp;
found, covering nearly all areas of the

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:16.400
nearshore seabed. As the preferred habitat of the&nbsp;
Dugong and hundreds of fish species, they also

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:21.920
provide a substantial carbon sink in regional&nbsp;
soil. Complementing these underwater meadows,

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:26.880
the UAE's coastline is also distinguished by&nbsp;
extensive mangrove forests that are locally known

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:32.880
as Qurm. These salt-tolerant trees, covering over&nbsp;
4,000 hectares nationally, create dense coastal

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:39.040
woodlands that serve as nurseries for marine life&nbsp;
and natural barriers against coastal erosion.

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:44.160
Like many marine habitats though, the changing&nbsp;
climate and warming waters are challnénging the

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:49.069
balance of this biosphere, but the mangroves 
and seagrass meadows are far from

00:05:49.069 --> 00:05:52.432
the most threatened coastal habitat of the UAE.

00:05:52.432 --> 00:05:57.680
This unfortunate status goes to the coral reefs&nbsp;
scattered along the UAE's shoreline and around its

00:05:57.680 --> 00:06:04.400
Gulf islands. When mapping of coral reefs started&nbsp;
in the 1960s, the coastal waters of the UAE were

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:10.160
renowned for their dense reefs spanning hundreds&nbsp;
of hectares and high percentage of alive corals

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:16.640
exceeding 60%. As time progressed and the oceans&nbsp;
warmed however, the habitats have been decimated,

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:23.040
and in 1998 they experienced another devastating&nbsp;
blow. During an extreme El Niño event, the Persian

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:28.960
Gulf temperatures reached unprecedented levels,&nbsp;
exceeding 37°C for extended periods, which led to

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:34.880
70% of the remaining corals expelled their symbiotic&nbsp;
algae in a process called coral bleaching.

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:39.600
To counteract this ecological collapse, the&nbsp;
UAE has launched an ambitious coral restoration

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:44.720
project, installing artificial reef modules&nbsp;
along much of the northwestern coastline. These

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:48.981
structures are seeded with coral fragments from&nbsp;
the most heat-resistant species, 

00:06:48.981 --> 00:06:51.520
cultivated in specialized nurseries in the UAE. 

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:56.400
While these restoration efforts represent genuine&nbsp;
attempts to address the environmental damage,

00:06:56.400 --> 00:07:01.760
they also serve broader strategic interests&nbsp;
that extend beyond ecological conservation.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:06.160
The discussion of UAE geography would&nbsp;
be incomplete without examining the oil

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:08.800
wealth that fundamentally transformed this region,

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:14.000
and of course the story of how they are trying&nbsp;
to diversify away from this finite resource.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.480
Starting in the 1950s, the first major oil&nbsp;
deposits were discovered in the desert of

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:23.840
Abu Dhabi, and its revenue has almost instantly&nbsp;
revolutionized the urban landscape and influence

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:29.840
of the UAE. The wealth has been used for ambitious&nbsp;
infrastructure projects and lavish skylines

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:34.880
but the government is aware that the oil&nbsp;
sources and global needs of oil are finite.

00:07:34.880 --> 00:07:39.120
Since then, the UAE has spent hundreds of&nbsp;
billions of US dollars to diversify the

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:43.520
country's industries, with tourism emerging&nbsp;
as one of the cornerstones of the strategy,

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:47.680
which explains the immense investments&nbsp;
put into the coral reefs for example.

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:52.640
Looking at the geographical distribution&nbsp;
of global oil reserves reveals just how

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:57.120
fortunate the emirates are positioned on&nbsp;
the world map, with nearly 6% of the global

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:04.480
oil reserves being contained in the 0.05% of&nbsp;
the global land area that the UAE occupies.

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:09.760
Most of the oil is located in the Zakum oil&nbsp;
field approximately 80 kilometers offshore

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:15.680
of the capital Abu Dhabi and many smaller oil fields&nbsp;
like the Umm Shaif, the Bu Hasa and the Habshan

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:22.080
oil fields all also holding significant reserves.
To this day, revenues from the oil are surging

00:08:22.080 --> 00:08:27.680
and increased focus on improving the value chain&nbsp;
of the oil, with new capabilities for refineries,

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:32.240
are increasing profit margins year over year.&nbsp;
Much of this wealth has been channeled into

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:36.960
the dramatic urban development visible across&nbsp;
Dubai and Abu Dhabi's skylines and coastlines,

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:41.680
establishing these cities as global centers&nbsp;
of commerce, tourism, and logistics.

00:08:41.680 --> 00:08:45.760
However, noteworthy places to visit extend&nbsp;
beyond the shimmering skyscrapers and

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:50.480
artificial islands of these metropolitan&nbsp;
hubs. Opposing high-tech and modernism,

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:55.680
the 5 easternmost emirates of the Union preserve&nbsp;
a lot more of the traditional architecture and

00:08:55.680 --> 00:09:01.520
Emirati heritage, bringing us to the last stop&nbsp;
of our journey around the United Arab Emirates.

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:07.040
Rising above Ras Al Khaimah, the easternmost&nbsp;
Emirati city on the Persian Gulf are the Hajar

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:12.880
Mountains. Although not particularly tall by&nbsp;
global standards, the contrast between them and

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:18.240
the endless desert to the west show quite the&nbsp;
contrasting stories. Located primarily within

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:23.440
Oman, the UAE controls an approximately 80&nbsp;
kilometer wide corridor connecting the Rub

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:28.720
al Khali Desert with the Gulf of Oman, cutting&nbsp;
off Musandam from the rest of Oman. Within this

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:33.920
stretch, most of the Emiratis land mammal&nbsp;
species thrive, including Arabian wolves,

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:39.280
foxes, and wildcats that inhabit the higher&nbsp;
elevations. Especially in the ungated wilderness

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:44.080
zones in the Hatta Region and the Wadi Wurayah&nbsp;
National Park these predators and their prey

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:48.800
live relatively undisturbed in low numbers.
With increased elevation, the intense desert

00:09:48.800 --> 00:09:53.280
heat becomes a lot more tolerable with&nbsp;
the summits and high ridges experiencing a

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:58.160
consistent temperature difference of around&nbsp;
10°C compared to the surrounding desert

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:03.280
This also allows some vegetation to establish&nbsp;
themselves on the mountain slopes with Sidr,

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:08.880
Juniper and other fruit trees occurring naturally&nbsp;
at higher elevations. Another factor for their

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:13.760
survival is the increased rainfall which&nbsp;
is caused by orographic precipitation. The

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:19.280
sharp rise of the mountains from the Gulf of Oman&nbsp;
elevates hot and moist air from the Indian Ocean,

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:25.280
which cools down and condenses as it crosses the&nbsp;
Hajar Mountains, leading to occasional rainfall.

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:29.120
While modest by global standards, it is&nbsp;
significantly higher than in the western

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:34.080
desert. There are strong annual variations but&nbsp;
in wet years, precipitation over the mountains

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:40.800
can reach up to 400 to 500 mm per year which is&nbsp;
comparable to cities like Los Angeles or Madrid.

00:10:40.800 --> 00:10:45.840
Despite the seasonal rain, rapid evaporation&nbsp;
prevents the formation of permanent streams

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:51.120
or natural lakes. Instead, the mountains are&nbsp;
drained by ephemeral streams called wadis,

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:56.800
which flow only during the rainy season. The&nbsp;
most significant examples include Wadi Bih,

00:10:56.800 --> 00:11:02.320
which drains the northernmost section of the UAE,&nbsp;
and Wadi Wurayah, which carries water from the

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:07.920
central mountains eastward to the Gulf of Oman.
Zooming out a bit and adding the interior borders

00:11:07.920 --> 00:11:12.160
of the UAE onto the map, the Western Hajar&nbsp;
mountains tell another interesting story

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:17.840
about their political subdivision. The cluster&nbsp;
of borders may appear like a dozen emirates being

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:23.520
spread across the mountains but the situation is a&nbsp;
bit more complicated than that. Five of the seven

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:28.400
Emirates, are holding territory in the Hajar&nbsp;
Mountains, yet not a single one of them forms

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:33.920
a continuous area. The most fractured of these&nbsp;
is Sharjah, which has its capital next to Dubai

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:39.440
along the Persian Gulf and then controls 5 more&nbsp;
disconnected territories in the Hajar Mountains.

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:45.200
The most peculiar of these enclaves is the village&nbsp;
of Nahwa, which is located entirely within Oman,

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:50.560
which itself again is an enclave entirely&nbsp;
surrounded by the UAE. While these rather chaotic

00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:55.520
borders appear quite random at first glance, they&nbsp;
have quite the reasonable historical background,

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:59.440
and should have been applied in many more&nbsp;
instances across the globe. During the

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:04.880
formation of and delimitation of the UAE and its&nbsp;
subdivisions, tribal affiliations were preserved

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:10.720
and respected, creating this now unique mosaic.
The emirate with the largest share of the Hajar

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:15.600
Mountains is Ras Al Khaimah, spread over two&nbsp;
extensive areas. Within this mountainous domain

00:12:15.600 --> 00:12:22.480
stands the region's crown jewel, the Jebel 
Jais. Standing at 1,934 meters above sea level,

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:27.440
it represents the highest point of the Western&nbsp;
Hajar range. Although the peak itself lies

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:33.360
just across the border in Oman, the UAE's highest&nbsp;
elevation is found on Jebel Jais's western slopes

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:40.960
at 1,892 meters and presents a fitting culmination&nbsp;
to our journey through the United Arab Emirates.

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:45.200
Looking back down from the ridges of the&nbsp;
Hajar Mountains, the uninterrupted view

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:48.960
over the flat desert landscape with one&nbsp;
of the most challenging climates in the

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:54.960
world is a statement of human resilience and&nbsp;
adaptability. Transformed by recent oil wealth,

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:57.680
the Emirates have undergone&nbsp;
unprecedented development,

00:12:57.680 --> 00:13:02.880
yet their future remains intricately tied&nbsp;
to both the finite oil reserves and the region's

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:08.240
harsh environmental constraints. As this small&nbsp;
nation continues to navigate between natural

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:14.720
limitations and ambitious modernization, its&nbsp;
geographical story remains far from complete.

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:17.680
If you want to see more mini documentaries&nbsp;
about the most extreme

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:23.120
places on planet earth, I can recommend this video&nbsp;
about the Geography of the Caucasus Mountains,

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:27.122
or watch what YouTube thinks is best for&nbsp;
you here. See you in the next one, 

00:13:27.122 --> 00:13:29.122
cheers.

